I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve the API data using the default URL parameter. This is the first step in the workflow to fetch the unknown data.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll use the data_processing_validator tool to validate the structure of the fetched API data. Since we don't have a specific schema, I'll use a generic validation approach with default parameters.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "data": {
        "type": "array"
      }
    },
    "required": ["data"]
  },
  "data": {},
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            The validation operation timed out. I'll retry the validation with a simpler schema and reduced timeout to prevent the same issue. I'll help us at least get basic validation results.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object"
  },
  "data": {},
  "options": {
    "timeout": 10
  }
}
</tool_call>

            I'll use the data_processing_parser tool to parse the validated data into a structured format. Since we don't have specific parsing requirements, I'll use default parameters.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

The parsing operation timed out. I'll retry with a reduced timeout and simpler parsing options to ensure completion. This is the final processing step in our workflow.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {
    "timeout": 15,
    "simple_parse": true
  }
}
</tool_call>

Since the parser failed again, I'll attempt to use the data_processing_transformer tool as an alternative approach to process the data, using the most basic transformation settings.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "input_format": "json",
  "output_format": "json",
  "options": {
    "timeout": 15,
    "simple_transform": true
  }
}
</tool_call>
